children.subject: Thank you! Do you think it would complement 162 and 127 (and nothing else) well? I've taken 3 techs before and I'll have taken 189 before I take this class.

I haven't taken 127, so I can't speak on that course and how it meshes, but I can say that 162 is also similar in that there is no weekly work but just heavy projects and heavier assignments than usual for upper division classes. I didn't take the two in the same semester so I don't know how the timeline matches up, but if you have projects/assignments in both classes at the same time, it might be a little tough on you, but I doubt that happens, and both classes are pretty good overall about assigning assignments/projects early so if you coordinate well, you will probably be fine.

I know that 194-129 counts as an upper division course for EECS, and it is generally 4 units. In terms of course structure, this past semester, there were 4 assignments, 2 midterms, and a final project. Each of these sections makes up 30% of the grade and then there's a 10% participation grade. Overall, the workload for most of the assignments is at a medium-level upper-division class but if you're new to Tensorflow it might be quite a bit more than that even for some of the others. The midterms are straightforward exams and are heavily based on lectures primarily so make sure to attend/watch lectures, and the final project is the most exciting part of the class and for me was very rewarding and engaging! So overall, the workload is not too high since there are only 4 assignments the entire semester and the final project only picks up last 1.5 months of the semester. Would highly recommend this class!

Hmm that's interesting. From what I could find online with previous syllabi for the classes, Professor Song's version of the class was 3 units. It seemed to be more paper focused, though with a similar workload. From what I've seen about Professor Canny's version, it seems to be 4 units and more about designing and applying knowledge of deep neural networks. Both are scheduled to be taught next spring.
You are referring to 194-131, which is not the same as 194-33.
I believe 194-33 will be the same as 194-129; last I talked to Prof. Canny he said he was going to hand the course off to Prof. Song to teach next year
